equation_narrative.headline: N-terminal position encoding drives immediate methionine recognition from layer 11
equation_narrative.story: Position 1 is the N-terminus of ubiquitin, a structural context that ESM-2 recognizes immediately. Early layers (1-10) show scattered logit-lens signals across polar and charged residues (S, H, Q, K) as the model reads local sequence context. At layer 11, the representation abruptly shifts to methionine (83.6%), reflecting the model's recognition of N-terminal position encoding—a feature strongly associated with methionine in protein sequences. From L11-23, the model assembles structural contacts (6 residues) and refines the representation to 93% methionine. The decision phase (L24-33) is remarkably stable: MLP neurons and attention features consistently reinforce methionine, reaching 99% confidence by L33.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-10 show the model reading local sequence context (MQIFVK) without clear biochemical interpretation—the logit lens fluctuates through S, H, Q, K as generic polar/charged signals. At layer 11, a decisive shift occurs: methionine jumps from 6.75% to 83.6%, driven by attention heads reading structural contacts and N-terminal position features. Six structural contacts are assembled, though their specific chemistry is less important than the positional encoding. By layer 17, methionine reaches 89.3% and continues to 93% by L23. SAE features at L9 (F9:5728, F9:1281) and L18 (F18:7108, F18:9838) encode abstract positional and structural context rather than amino-acid-specific predictions.
perception_phase.context_character: The representation by L23 encodes N-terminal position (the defining feature), local hydrophobic context from adjacent residues (Q, I, F, V), and 6 structural contacts. The biochemical environment is moderately hydrophobic with nearby polar residues.
key_information_sources: N-terminal position encoding: the strongest signal, recognized by L11 and driving the methionine representation
Structural contacts: 6 residues within 8Å, read by attention heads at L8-12 (head 6 at L8 shows -1.647 projection, erasing early noise)
Local sequence: MQIFVK context provides hydrophobic character (I, F, V) adjacent to the masked position
Co-evolutionary signal: minimal (only 1 co-evolving position), suggesting this position is structurally constrained rather than functionally coupled

decision_phase.summary: The decision phase (L24-33) is unusually stable—methionine is already at 93% by L23 and the model simply reinforces this choice. Late-layer SAE features (F30:5397 with 23.56 projection, F33:4166 with 99.76 projection) act as methionine-specific prediction channels. MLP neurons at L27-32 show strong pro-methionine activity (N27:3452, N31:4039, N32:1865) while simultaneously suppressing alternatives through large erasure neurons (N27:706 with -1.523 projection against E/W/K, N32:3437 with -2.586 against D/P/G). The final layer (L33) shows massive MLP erasure (-10.33 delta) that paradoxically increases methionine confidence to 99.06% by eliminating residual noise.
decision_phase.transition: The L23-25 boundary shows minimal transition because the decision is effectively made by L11. At L24, SAE features shift from abstract positional encoding to amino-acid-specific prediction channels (F24:6298, F24:2220), but methionine is already dominant. The representation has encoded 'N-terminal position' since L11, which is functionally equivalent to 'methionine' in the model's learned statistics.

candidates.narrative: Methionine emerges decisively at L11 (83.6%) when the model recognizes N-terminal position encoding, the strongest predictor of methionine in protein sequences. From L11-23, structural contacts and local hydrophobic context refine the representation to 93%. In the decision phase, methionine-specific prediction channels activate: F30:5397 (23.56 projection), F33:4166 (99.76 projection), and MLP neurons N27:3452 (0.942 projection), N31:4039 (0.815), N32:1865 (1.226). The model reaches 99.06% confidence by L33, with massive MLP erasure in the final layer eliminating all alternatives.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges at L11 (83.6%), dominant through L17-33 (89-99%)
key_evidence: F33:4166 (attn, 99.76 proj) — methionine-specific prediction channel at final layer
N32:1865 (1.226 proj) — strongest MLP writer for M, also votes for I/V (hydrophobic alternatives)
N27:706 (-1.523 proj) — massive eraser suppressing E/W/K to clear space for M
Attention head L31:15 (3.45 proj) — late structural writer reinforcing M

candidates.narrative: Isoleucine is the only viable alternative, peaking briefly at L31 (7.69%) before settling at 0.67%. It receives support from hydrophobic-voting MLP neurons (N32:1865 votes 0.913 for I, N26:3669 votes 0.585 for I) because it shares methionine's hydrophobic character and fits the local context (adjacent I, F, V residues). However, isoleucine lacks the N-terminal position encoding that drives methionine, and late-layer erasure neurons suppress it along with other alternatives.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks at L31 (7.69%), suppressed by L33 (0.67%)
key_evidence: N26:3669 (0.405 proj for M, 0.585 for I) — hydrophobic neuron voting for both M and I
N32:1865 (0.913 proj for I) — same neuron that writes M also supports I as hydrophobic alternative

candidates.narrative: Lysine leads the logit lens at L4-10 (peaking at 21.5% at L10) not because the model predicts lysine, but because the early representation encodes generic 'charged/polar' character from reading the local sequence context (Q at position 2, K at position 6). This is a logit-lens artifact: the intermediate representation happens to project toward charged residues before the model has assembled enough information to recognize N-terminal position. Lysine is eliminated by L11 when methionine surges to 83.6%.
candidates.key_layers: Leads L4-10 (peaks at 21.5%), eliminated by L11
key_evidence: Early SAE features F1:5480, F1:9146 encode generic sequence context, not K-specific prediction
Attention head L8:6 (-1.647 proj) erases early noise including K signal

candidates.narrative: Valine shows 12.17% in the initial embedding (L0) and decays rapidly, reflecting the logit lens projecting the raw embedding through the unembedding matrix before any contextual processing. This is pure artifact—the embedding space happens to have some overlap with valine's direction. Valine receives scattered support from hydrophobic MLP neurons (N21:2592 votes 0.285 for V) but never competes seriously once N-terminal encoding is recognized.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks at L0 (12.17%), decays by L8 (2.37%)
key_evidence: L0 embedding artifact, no mechanistic support
N21:2592 (0.285 proj for V) — weak hydrophobic voting, insufficient to compete with M

turning_points.description: The decisive turning point occurs at L11 when methionine surges from 6.75% to 83.6%. This is driven by the model recognizing N-terminal position encoding—a feature strongly associated with methionine in protein sequences. MLP neurons at L10-11 show mixed activity (L10 total: +1.64, L11 total: -0.54), but attention heads are reading structural contacts and assembling the positional context. The velocity event at L11 is not captured in the top events, but the lead change from K (21.5%) to M (83.6%) marks the moment when abstract positional features dominate over local sequence chemistry.

A brief destabilization occurs at L19-21 with negative velocity events (-3.02, -2.61, -2.60 total delta) driven by both attention and MLP. The logit lens shows methionine dipping slightly from 89.3% at L17 to a local minimum around L20 before recovering. This appears to be the model refining its structural contact interpretation—attention heads are re-weighting the 6 structural contacts, and MLP neurons (N19:3113 with -0.231 projection, N20:3080 with -0.483) are suppressing hydrophobic alternatives (F, C, Y) that might fit the local chemistry but not the N-terminal constraint.

The final commitment occurs at L31-33 with massive attention writing (L31:15 head with 3.45 projection, L32:18 head with 1.928 projection) and extreme MLP activity. At L32, MLP neurons show -10.37 total projection with enormous erasure (N32:3437 erases -2.586 against D/P/G, N32:4115 erases -1.347 against V/F/W) while simultaneously writing for M (N32:1865 writes +1.226). The final layer (L33) shows +8.45 total delta with attention writing +6.74 and MLP erasing -10.33, paradoxically increasing methionine to 99.06% by eliminating all residual probability mass from alternatives.

deep_dives.label: SAE features L1-9: position encoding
deep_dives.caption: Early SAE features encode abstract sequence and positional context rather than amino-acid predictions. F1:5480, F1:9146, F1:1508 (all ~44 projection) represent generic sequence reading. By L9, features like F9:5728 (51.64 proj) encode more refined structural context that will enable N-terminal recognition at L11.

deep_dives.label: Structural attention L8-12
deep_dives.caption: Attention heads at L8-12 read the 6 structural contacts and assemble N-terminal position encoding. Head L8:6 shows -1.647 projection (structural eraser), clearing early noise. The decisive shift at L11 (K→M lead change) is driven by these heads recognizing the N-terminal context.

deep_dives.label: MLP neurons L10-14: M emergence
deep_dives.caption: MLP neurons at L10-14 show the transition from scattered voting to methionine commitment. L10 shows mixed activity (+1.64 total), L11 shows net erasure (-0.54) as alternatives are suppressed, then L12-14 show strong pro-M neurons (N12:3486, N13:2322, N14:4595) emerging alongside erasers targeting polar/charged alternatives.

deep_dives.label: SAE features L30-33: M prediction channels
deep_dives.caption: Late SAE features are methionine-specific prediction channels. F30:5397 (23.56 proj), F33:4166 (99.76 proj), F33:6423 (98.92 proj) show extreme projections, acting as dedicated M detectors that fire when all contextual evidence (N-terminal position, hydrophobic environment, structural contacts) aligns.

deep_dives.label: MLP neurons L27-32: final decision
deep_dives.caption: Late MLP neurons show extreme activity: strong M writers (N27:3452 with 0.942, N31:4039 with 0.815, N32:1865 with 1.226) compete with massive erasers (N27:706 with -1.523 against E/W/K, N32:3437 with -2.586 against D/P/G). The net effect is to drive M to 99%+ confidence by eliminating all alternatives.

deep_dives.label: Velocity events L19-21: refinement
deep_dives.caption: L19-21 shows negative velocity (-3.02, -2.61, -2.60) as the model refines its structural interpretation. Both attention and MLP contribute to suppressing hydrophobic alternatives (F, C, Y) that fit local chemistry but not N-terminal constraints. This is a quality-control phase before final commitment.

equation_narrative.resolution: ESM-2 correctly predicts methionine with 99% confidence by recognizing N-terminal position encoding—the dominant signal for this position. The model assembles this context by layer 11, when methionine surges from 7% to 84% in the logit lens. The 6 structural contacts and local hydrophobic context (MQIFVK) provide supporting evidence, but the N-terminal position is decisive. Late-layer MLP neurons and SAE features act as methionine-specific prediction channels, reinforcing the choice while massive erasure neurons eliminate alternatives. The prediction is overdetermined: N-terminal position alone is sufficient, and the structural/chemical context aligns perfectly.
